To find the effective resistance between two nodes, you would have to
swap the 1st and sixth columns to the 1 and 2 positions inside the
Laplacian matrix. You would then break up this Laplacian matrix into a
block matrix\begin{align*}
L = \begin{bmatrix}
A & B^{T} \\
B & C 
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*} where $A$ will be a 2x2 matrix.

You would then find the voltage to current map (A.K.A Schur$^{\prime}$s
complement), matrix S whose equation is\begin{align*}
S = A - B^{T} C^{-1} B
\end{align*}

Then, after solving for S, the effective resistance would be the
reciprocal of the 1st entry of matrix S.

MATLAB CODE:

\texttt{~~~\%nodes~n~and~m~position}\\\texttt{~~~n~=~1;}\\\texttt{~~~m~=~6;}\\\texttt{~~~}\\\texttt{~~~\%find~the~size~of~the~matrix~L}\\\texttt{~~~lenL~=~length(L);}\\\texttt{~~~}\\\texttt{~~~\%swap~nodes~n~and~m~to~the~1st~and~2nd~position~in~the~Laplacian~matrix}\\\texttt{~~~swap~=~{[}n,~m,~1:(n-1),~(n+1):(m-1),~(m+1):lenL{]};}\\\texttt{~~~L~=~L(swap,~swap);}\\\texttt{~~~}\\\texttt{~~~\%compute~matrix~S~which~is~the~voltage~to~current~map~(Schur's~complement).}\\\texttt{~~~A~=~L((1:2),~(1:2));}\\\texttt{~~~B~=~L((3:lenL),~(1:2));}\\\texttt{~~~C~=~L((3:lenL),~(3:lenL));}\\\texttt{~~~S~=~A~-~(B}$^{\prime}$\texttt{~*~C}\textsuperscript{\texttt{(}}\texttt{-1)~*~B);}\\\texttt{~~~}\\\texttt{~~~\%finds~the~effective~resistance~which~is~the~first~entry~of~S.}\\\texttt{~~~r~=~1/S(1,1);}

You could run this for the 2 different Laplacian matrices to find the
effective resistance for each and compare them to confirm the conjecture
is correct.

sols_raw:
To find the effective resistance between two nodes, you would have to swap the 1st and sixth columns to the 1 and 2 positions inside the Laplacian matrix. You would then break up this Laplacian matrix into a block matrix: &lt;math>L = \begin{bmatrix}
A &amp; B^{T} \\
B &amp; C 
\end{bmatrix}&lt;/math> where &lt;math>A&lt;/math> will be a 2x2 matrix.

You would then find the voltage to current map (A.K.A Schur’s complement), matrix S whose equation is: &lt;math>S = A - B^{T} C^{-1} B&lt;/math>

Then, after solving for S, the effective resistance would be the reciprocal of the 1st entry of matrix S.

MATLAB CODE:

    %nodes n and m position
    n = 1;
    m = 6;

    %find the size of the matrix L
    lenL = length(L);

    %swap nodes n and m to the 1st and 2nd position in the Laplacian matrix
    swap = [n, m, 1:(n-1), (n+1):(m-1), (m+1):lenL];
    L = L(swap, swap);

    %compute matrix S which is the voltage to current map (Schur's complement).
    A = L((1:2), (1:2));
    B = L((3:lenL), (1:2));
    C = L((3:lenL), (3:lenL));
    S = A - (B’ * C&lt;sup>(&lt;/sup>-1) * B);

    %finds the effective resistance which is the first entry of S.
    r = 1/S(1,1);

You could run this for the 2 different Laplacian matrices to find the effective resistance for each and compare them to confirm the conjecture is correct.
